docs.abstract: Once wildly popular for its inexpensive, imported pillows and rattan chairs, the home furnishings chain struggled to compete against Home Goods and Etsy.
docs.snippet: Once wildly popular for its inexpensive, imported pillows and rattan chairs, the home furnishings chain struggled to compete against Home Goods and Etsy.
docs.lead_paragraph: Pier 1 Imports, the home goods retailer that in the 1990s became a popular destination for exotic rattan chairs and cheap embroidered pillows only to cede its market niche over the last decade to lower-priced competitors, announced on Monday that it had filed for bankruptcy and was pursuing a sale of the company.

headline.main: Pier 1 Imports, the Struggling Home Goods Retailer, Files for Bankruptcy
headline.print_headline: Pier 1 Imports Files for Bankruptcy After a Failed Attempt at a Turnaround

byline.original: By Natasha Singer and Heather Murphy

docs.abstract: A fraught moment for a newsroom that, its editor in chief says, will not do in-depth investigations of Mike Bloomberg or any other Democrats running for president.
docs.snippet: A fraught moment for a newsroom that, its editor in chief says, will not do in-depth investigations of Mike Bloomberg or any other Democrats running for president.
docs.lead_paragraph: Get ready to cover the boss’s presidential campaign, with some caveats.

headline.print_headline: How Media Firm Will Cover Boss

docs.abstract: The dollar is the strongest it has been in nearly three years as global investors seek a safe haven. But that can have unwelcome effects for U.S. industries.
docs.snippet: The dollar is the strongest it has been in nearly three years as global investors seek a safe haven. But that can have unwelcome effects for U.S. industries.
docs.lead_paragraph: The dollar climbed to its highest level in years this week, a reflection of the standout status of the American economy against a global backdrop clouded by the coronavirus.

headline.main: Surging Dollar Reflects the Standout U.S. Economy
headline.print_headline: Dollar Soars  On Worries  About Effects  Of a Virus

docs.abstract: Donations to the public broadcaster went up sharply after the president said it was “a very good question” to ask why it still existed.
docs.snippet: Donations to the public broadcaster went up sharply after the president said it was “a very good question” to ask why it still existed.
docs.lead_paragraph: First President Trump questioned the existence of National Public Radio in a tweet. Then, as part of the annual budget request released last Monday, he recommended slashing federal funding to the Corporation for Public Broadcasting, the body that distributes taxpayer dollars to NPR and other public media outlets, to $0 by 2023.

headline.main: Unloved by Trump, NPR Carries On
headline.print_headline: NPR, Under Attack by Trump, Is Taking the Threat Seriously

docs.abstract: A federal watchdog says the agency allowed 150,000 flights on planes that had not been proved airworthy.
docs.snippet: A federal watchdog says the agency allowed 150,000 flights on planes that had not been proved airworthy.
docs.lead_paragraph: Regulators failed to hold Southwest Airlines to account for not meeting safety standards, putting as many as 17 million passengers at risk on tens of thousands of flights, a federal watchdog said in a report on Tuesday.

headline.main: F.A.A. Failed to Assure Southwest Airlines Safety, Report Says
headline.print_headline: Inquiry Finds Safety Failures By the F.A.A. And Southwest

docs.abstract: The virus could affect the global economy, the Federal Reserve head told Congress. He also signaled comfort with leaving interest rates unchanged.
docs.snippet: The virus could affect the global economy, the Federal Reserve head told Congress. He also signaled comfort with leaving interest rates unchanged.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Federal Reserve chair, Jerome H. Powell, warned lawmakers on Tuesday that the coronavirus epidemic sweeping China could pose broader economic risks, even as he signaled that the central bank was comfortable holding interest rates steady for now.

headline.main: Powell, Warning of a Possible Virus Fallout, Is Slammed Again by Trump
headline.print_headline: Powell Warns of Fallout From Virus

docs.abstract: The agency ordered Amazon, Apple, Facebook, Alphabet and Microsoft to turn over a decade’s worth of information on small acquisitions.
docs.snippet: The agency ordered Amazon, Apple, Facebook, Alphabet and Microsoft to turn over a decade’s worth of information on small acquisitions.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Federal Trade Commission said on Tuesday that it had ordered Amazon, Apple, Facebook, Google’s parent company and Microsoft to turn over information about past acquisitions, broadening its review of the power of big tech companies.

headline.main: F.T.C. Broadens Review of Tech Giants, Homing In on Their Deals
headline.print_headline: F.T.C. Aims To Take Look Down Gullet Of Big Tech

docs.abstract: Biometric sensors are getting lighter, cheaper and more accurate, and could help warn drivers before they become too fatigued.
docs.snippet: Biometric sensors are getting lighter, cheaper and more accurate, and could help warn drivers before they become too fatigued.
docs.lead_paragraph: Falling asleep at the wheel is a trucker’s worst nightmare. Fatigue comes with the job of driving an eighteen-wheeler, even with rules requiring rest stops and limiting driving hours. Now, new technologies are becoming available to alert drowsy drivers, sometimes even before they feel tired.

headline.main: Wearable Tech That Tells Drowsy Truckers It’s Time to Pull Over

docs.abstract: A new report points to a shortage of successful programs for tech careers. One, it says, shows how they can work.
docs.snippet: A new report points to a shortage of successful programs for tech careers. One, it says, shows how they can work.
docs.lead_paragraph: Tech jobs are coming to New York City in droves. All the big tech companies — even Amazon, which abandoned plans for a headquarters-style campus a year ago — are expanding in the city.

headline.main: New Yorkers Face a Training Gap for Tech Jobs, but a Study Finds Hope
headline.print_headline: Tech Jobs Are Flocking to New York. Can Workers Snare Them?
